<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="growth-app-store-optimization">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>gtm-strategist</domain>
    <summary>Improve app visibility in App Store and Google Play through metadata, visuals, and reviews. Optimize keyword ranking and conversion rate together to maximize organic downloads.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>aso</tag>
      <tag>app-store</tag>
      <tag>keywords</tag>
      <tag>conversion</tag>
      <tag>mobile-marketing</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>App Store Optimization (ASO)</title>

    <summary>ASO is the discipline of improving app visibility in Apple App Store and Google Play through metadata, visual assets, and review strategy. It splits into two levers: visibility (keyword ranking) and conversion (listing page to download). Both must be optimized together. Organic search drives 65%+ of downloads, making ASO the highest-leverage discovery channel for mobile apps.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>App stores are the primary discovery channel for mobile apps — paid UA is expensive and unpredictable. Organic search drives 65%+ of downloads. Optimizing metadata, visuals, and reviews compounds over time: a higher-ranking listing converts better and earns more reviews, which improves ranking further.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Launching a new mobile app and setting up the store listing for the first time</item>
        <item>Organic downloads have plateaued despite active UA spend</item>
        <item>Conversion rate from store page view to download is below 30%</item>
        <item>Expanding into new language markets (localization)</item>
        <item>After a major product update that adds keyword-relevant features</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Web apps, PWAs, or desktop software — wrong channel entirely</item>
        <item>App has fewer than 50 weekly organic impressions — too early; fix product-market fit first</item>
        <item>B2B enterprise apps distributed via MDM — discovery is sales-led, not store-driven</item>
        <item>When budget for new screenshots/video does not exist — visual improvement is the highest-ROI ASO lever and skipping it limits results</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="ios-ranking-factors">
      <p>Apple's algorithm weights title and subtitle fields most heavily. Keywords appearing here rank faster and higher than those only in the keywords field. Duplicating name/subtitle terms in the keywords field wastes scarce characters. Apple pluralizes singular terms automatically, so adding plural forms is redundant.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Place primary keyword in app name (30 chars) and subtitle (30 chars) — these carry the highest weight in iOS ranking.</statement>
        <rationale>Apple's algorithm weights title and subtitle fields most heavily. Keywords appearing here rank faster and higher than those only in the keywords field.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use the 100-character iOS keywords field for secondary terms only: no spaces, comma-separated, no duplicates of name/subtitle, singular only (Apple auto-pluralizes).</statement>
        <rationale>Duplicating name/subtitle terms in the keywords field wastes scarce characters. Apple pluralizes singular terms automatically, so adding plural forms is redundant.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="google-play-ranking-factors">
      <p>Google Play indexes the full description as a web document. Keyword density and placement in the short description (shown in search results) directly affect ranking.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Place primary keyword in the first sentence of the Google Play short description (80 chars) and repeat key terms 3–5 times naturally in the full description (4000 chars).</statement>
        <rationale>Google Play indexes the full description as a web document. Keyword density and placement in the short description (shown in search results) directly affect ranking.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="keyword-research-process">
      <p>Single-source research misses long-tail terms that competitors haven't targeted. Review mining surfaces the words actual users use — often different from marketing language. Score every keyword candidate on relevance, volume, and difficulty before prioritizing, targeting high-relevance, medium-difficulty keywords first.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Research keywords from five sources before writing any metadata: competitor analysis, store autocomplete, review mining, related searches, and ASO tools (Sensor Tower, AppTweak, data.ai).</statement>
        <rationale>Single-source research misses long-tail terms that competitors haven't targeted. Review mining surfaces the words actual users use — often different from marketing language.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Score every keyword candidate on relevance (0–10), volume (High/Med/Low), and difficulty (High/Med/Low) before prioritizing. Target high-relevance, medium-difficulty keywords first.</statement>
        <rationale>High-volume keywords are dominated by top apps. Medium-difficulty keywords offer ranking opportunity while still delivering meaningful traffic.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="controllable-vs-uncontrollable-factors">
      <p>Fully controllable: name, subtitle/short description, keywords field, full description, icon, screenshots, video. Partially controllable: download velocity (via UA spend), ratings (via review prompts), engagement metrics (via UX quality). Not controllable: competitor activity, algorithm changes.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="app-icon-rules">
      <p>Icons render at 29x29 pixels in some placements. Text becomes unreadable. Single-element icons are recognized faster in peripheral vision and crowded search results.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Design icon with one focal element, no text, and brand colors. A/B test at least two variants before finalizing.</statement>
        <rationale>Icons render at 29x29 pixels in some placements. Text becomes unreadable. Single-element icons are recognized faster in peripheral vision and crowded search results.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="screenshot-rules">
      <p>Eye-tracking studies show 60%+ of store visitors view only the first two screenshots. Burying the key feature in screenshot 4 costs conversion from the majority of visitors. Text overlay explains what the user sees. Empty states (blank dashboards, sign-up screens) communicate nothing about the product's value. Inconsistent screenshots signal a low-quality or abandoned product and reduce trust.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>First two screenshots must show the core value proposition — assume most visitors never scroll to screenshot 3+.</statement>
        <rationale>Eye-tracking studies show 60%+ of store visitors view only the first two screenshots. Burying the key feature in screenshot 4 costs conversion from the majority of visitors.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Add a benefit headline as text overlay on each screenshot. Show the app in active use, not empty states.</statement>
        <rationale>Text overlay explains what the user sees. Empty states (blank dashboards, sign-up screens) communicate nothing about the product's value.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use consistent visual style across all screenshots (same font, color palette, device frame).</statement>
        <rationale>Inconsistent screenshots signal a low-quality or abandoned product and reduce trust.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="preview-video-rules">
      <p>Most users autoplay with sound off. Narration adds nothing. The first 3 seconds determine whether the viewer continues; starting with a menu screen or splash animation loses viewers immediately.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep preview video to 15–30 seconds. Hook in first 3 seconds. Show real app usage only. No narration.</statement>
        <rationale>Most users autoplay with sound off. Narration adds nothing. The first 3 seconds determine whether the viewer continues; starting with a menu screen or splash animation loses viewers immediately.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="before-after-conversion-example">
      <p>Visual optimization compounds over time. Higher conversion rates lead to more downloads, which trigger more reviews, improving ranking, which increases visibility and download velocity further.</p>

      <example type="bad" title="Before optimization">
        <note>Before optimization: generic name, vague subtitle, narrow keyword set, low review count.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Name: MyApp
Subtitle: The best app
Keywords: productivity,work,business
Rating: 3.8 stars (50 reviews)
Conversion (page view → download): ~20%
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="After optimization">
        <note>After optimization: keyword in name, benefit subtitle, expanded keyword field, review prompt added. Results: 3x organic downloads, 40% conversion, top 10 for "todo list".</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Name: MyApp - Task Manager
Subtitle: To-do lists & productivity
Keywords: todo,checklist,planner,organize,tasks,reminder,daily,habit
Rating: 4.6 stars (500 reviews)
Conversion (page view → download): ~50%
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="review-acquisition">
      <p>Early prompts interrupt onboarding and elicit neutral/negative reviews from users who haven't experienced value. Post-positive-action timing captures peak satisfaction. Review gating (only showing the store prompt to users who said they liked the app) is banned on both platforms and can result in removal.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Trigger in-app review prompt only after a positive action (task completed, goal reached) and after the user's 3rd+ session. Never prompt on first launch or after negative events.</statement>
        <rationale>Early prompts interrupt onboarding and elicit neutral/negative reviews from users who haven't experienced value. Post-positive-action timing captures peak satisfaction.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Apple's SKStoreReviewRequest API (iOS) or Google's In-App Review API (Android) — do not build custom review gates or incentivize reviews. Both are policy violations.</statement>
        <rationale>Review gating (only showing the store prompt to users who said they liked the app) is banned on both platforms and can result in removal.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="negative-review-response">
      <p>Public responses demonstrate support quality to prospective users scanning reviews. Users who see a thoughtful response are more likely to update their rating. App stores surface developer responses prominently.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Respond to all negative reviews within 24 hours: acknowledge the issue, describe the fix or workaround, and ask the user to update their review if the issue is resolved.</statement>
        <rationale>Public responses demonstrate support quality to prospective users scanning reviews. Users who see a thoughtful response are more likely to update their rating. App stores surface developer responses prominently.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <templates>
        <template path="templates/review-response.txt" purpose="Negative review response template with variable fields"/>
      </templates>
    </section>

    <section name="localization-priority">
      <p>These locales represent the largest App Store revenue pools. Translating only the description while keeping English screenshots leaves 30–50% of conversion potential unrealized in non-English markets.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Localize in this order: English (US/UK), Spanish (LATAM + Spain), Portuguese (Brazil), German (DACH), French, Japanese, Korean, Chinese (Simplified). Localize name, subtitle, description, screenshot text overlays, and keyword field for each locale.</statement>
        <rationale>These locales represent the largest App Store revenue pools. Translating only the description while keeping English screenshots leaves 30–50% of conversion potential unrealized in non-English markets.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Keyword stuffing: packing keywords unnaturally into the description or name (e.g., "todo task list checklist planner reminder organizer").</description>
        <reason>Both stores penalize unnatural keyword repetition. Human-readable copy converts better and avoids algorithmic penalties.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Ignoring reviews for more than 48 hours.</description>
        <reason>Unanswered negative reviews accumulate in visible positions and signal poor support. The window to convert a negative reviewer to a neutral one closes quickly.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Never updating the store listing after launch.</description>
        <reason>Both stores factor update frequency into ranking. Stale listings signal abandonment and hurt position over time.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/listing-checklist.md" purpose="iOS and Google Play metadata + visual asset checklist per submission"/>
      <template path="templates/aso-audit.md" purpose="Audit template: current state, competitor analysis, opportunities, recommendations"/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://developer.apple.com/app-store/product-page/"/>
      <link href="https://developer.android.com/distribute/best-practices/launch/store-listing"/>
      <link href="https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appstoreconnectapi"/>
      <link href="https://developers.google.com/android-publisher"/>
      <link href="https://docs.fastlane.tools"/>
      <link href="https://www.apptweak.com/en/aso-blog"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
